[1] India (Bangalore)
Date: Thu, 7 Jul 2005 17:26:03 +0200 (CEST)
From: Dr. Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Khaleej Times, UAE 7 Jul 2005 [edited]
<http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle.asp?xfile=data/subcontinent/2005/July/subcontinent_July222.xmlÂ§ion=subcontinent&col=>


Dengue fever scare plagues Bangalore
----------------------------------
Even as reports of deaths caused by dengue fever are coming in from
neighbouring Tumkur, hospitals in Bangalore have begun receiving several
cases of suspected dengue fever, causing an alarm among the public as well
as health officials.

The disease, which is caused by mosquitoes breeding in stagnant water,
commonly occurs after the monsoon has set in. People afflicted with dengue
show symptoms of fever, lower back ache, pain in the calf muscles and, in
some cases, nasal bleeding.

More than 50 patients have been admitted to Manipal Hospital in the city
for suspected dengue fever during the last couple of weeks. Even the St
Philomena's Hospital received several cases of suspected dengue fever.
Though no deaths on account of dengue have been reported in Bangalore, 5
patients are undergoing treatment for the same at St Philomena's Hospital.

"This is only the beginning. An increase in the number of cases can be seen
in the next 3 months after heavy rains have set in", say medical experts.

St. Johns Medical Hospital has confirmed one case of dengue fever reported
to them last week.

