[2] Philippines (Kidapawan City)
Date: Wed, 6 Jul 2005 03:19:26 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Minda News, Phillipines, 6 July 2005 [edited]
<http://www.mindanews.com/2005/07/05nws-dengue.html>


Continued dengue rise in North Cotabato blamed on uncooperative residents
--------------------------------------------------
Health authorities renewed their call on local government officials and
residents to help counter the increasing incidence of dengue, a disease
likely fatal in children.

The North Cotabato provincial dengue control and prevention division has
urged the 17 town mayors to help in their campaign against dengue.

Dra. Perlita Albano, the health officer of Kidapawan City, has attributed
the increase of dengue cases in the city's 3 barangays to the lack of
cooperation among residents, especially the implementation of 4 o'clock
habit in their areas. [From posting 20050519.1375: "..the 4 o'clock habit
... involved cleaning surroundings, draining of water accumulated in tires,
bottles, flower vases, and roof gutters to prevent mosquitoes from breeding."]

Kidapawan City posted the highest incidence of dengue [within the province
of North Cotabato. - Mod.RY].

Jun Mancao, dengue control and prevention in-charge of the province's
Department of Health [DOH], told DXND Radio for Peace that his office has
noted a dramatic rise of dengue cases in various town of the province.

DOH records show that 673 cases of confirmed dengue patients were admitted
in 5 government hospitals from January to June of the 2005. Kidapawan City
ranked number one with total cases of 189 cases, with 2 fatalities.

The remaining 484 cases were documented in the towns of M'lang, Matalam,
Makilala, Tulunan, and President Roxas in the 2nd district and in the town
of Banisilan, Pigcawayan and Midsayap.

Albano said the city's private hospitals reported 32 dengue patients in
June 2005, and that the majority came from Barangays Poblacion, Nuangan and
Ilomavis.

"We conduct inspections in these places, and we found breeding places of
mosquitoes, which is possibly the reason why increases in dengue cases in
these 3 barangays were noted," Albano told a regular session of the
Sangguniang Panglungsod.

Councilor Jonares John Amador passed a resolution asking City Mayor Rodolfo
Gantuangco to allocate funds for the massive information campaign in the
grassroots level.

His resolution said the city would tap non-government organizations, public
and private schools, barangay officials and all media organizations in the
city to help educate the residents on how to combat the deadly dengue fever.

Health Secretary Francisco Duque III has told a television interviews said
that there were 5396 dengue patients in various government hospitals
nationwide from January to 15 Jun 2005. There were 77 fatalities nationwide.

Duque attributed the increase to the onset of rainy season, with water
accumulated in junked tin cans, bottles, uncovered containers and clogged
gutters serving as breeding places for mosquitoes.

Dengue fever is a disease [spread] by _Aedes aegypti_, a day-biting
mosquito. Symptoms of dengue include fever, rashes, severe headache, muscle
and joint pains, loss of appetite and vomiting.

He said that the participation of the local authorities would significantly
reduce dengue cases.

Sec. Duque said the regions with the highest number of dengue cases were
Northern Mindanao with 1 242 cases, National Capital Region with 965 cases,
Caraga with 683 cases, and Central Luzon, with 603, and Central Visayas
with 579 cases.

