[4] Yemen (Correction: Saudi Arabia -- see PRO/ERR> Dengue/DHF update 2005 (19): correction 20050719.2078)
Date: Thu, 7 Jul 2005 17:51:06 +0300
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo <oshamsudeen@hotmail.com>
Source: The Saudi Gazette, 27 jun 2005 [edited]
<http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/sgazette/Data/2005/6/27/Art_236301.XML>


Dengue Fever Hits Jeddah; 20 Suffer
---------------------------------
More than 20 residents of Al-Muntazahat District in Jeddah have come down
with Dengue fever, the Arabic language daily newspaper, Al-Madina, reported.

The victims belong to 5 families living in close proximity. The owner of a
nearby building under construction, as well as its janitor and architect,
have also contracted the disease.

All patients are suffering from stomach pains, extremely high fever and
diarrhea. According to a source at the Ministry of Health, Dengue fever is
endemic in the districts of the Western Province.

Individuals who have come down with the disease have accused Jeddah
Municipality of being lax in spraying insecticides to exterminate
mosquitoes, which are the prime carriers of the disease.

Sources at the Environmental Health Department said that they have informed
municipal officials that Dengue fever is suspected.

[One male patient] said that he contracted the fever first, then his 2
wives. Ultimately he was admitted to hospital for more than 6 days, while
his 2 wives and children are still at King Fahd Military Hospital. "All of
my neighbors of all age groups have come down with the disease," he said.

[Another male patient -- a retiree --] said that he and his 8 children have
come down with the disease. A private hospital had diagnosed the case as
ordinary fever.

[Yet a 3rd patient] said that the virus has spread in their neighborhood
due to the accumulating litter and the fact that sewage water and drinking
water have mixed.

Awad Al-Maleki, an official at the Environmental Health Department in
Jeddah Governorate, said that the municipality is systematically spraying
all districts in Jeddah.

"We will also spray the district where the disease broke out in its
entirety this evening as a precautionary measure," he added.

The Head of Health Affairs in Jeddah, as well as his assistant for
preliminary health care Dr. Ashraf Al-Amir, could not be contacted to
comment on the issue.

--
Shamsudeen Fagbo
<oshamsudeen@hotmail.com>

